'''Ōbosan Kofun''' (王墓山古墳) is a Kofun located in {{ill|Kurashiki|ja|倉敷市|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, Nihata, Okayama Prefecture. It is part of the Ōbosan Kofun Cluster (or Akai Nishi Kofun Cluster) and is designated as a Historic Site of Okayama Prefecture.

== Overview ==
Ōbosan Kofun is situated on a low hill along the right bank of the Ashimori River. This area is known for its concentration of Kofuns, with Ōbosan Kofun serving as the primary tumulus of the cluster. The mound and burial chamber underwent significant alterations during the late Meiji period.

The original shape of the mound is estimated to have been either circular or square, with a diameter or side length of approximately 25 meters. The burial chamber was likely a horizontal stone chamber, although no trace of it remains today due to stone extraction. The site retains a house-shaped sarcophagus placed near the mound. The tumulus is dated to the late {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, around the late 6th century. The sarcophagus exhibits close similarities to that of the {{ill|Kōmorizuka Kofun|ja|こうもり塚古墳|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Sōja|ja|総社市|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, indicating a potential connection between the two sites.

Ōbosan Kofun was designated a Historic Site of Okayama Prefecture in 1959. Today, it is part of the Ōbo-no-Oka Historic Park and is open to the public.

== Burial Facility ==
The burial facility is presumed to have been a horizontal stone chamber. However, the chamber was destroyed during the late Meiji period for stone quarrying, and only the sarcophagus remains. The sarcophagus, crafted from shell limestone sourced from {{ill|Ibara, Okayama|ja|井原市|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, is a constructed house-shaped type comprising seven stone slabs. Its dimensions are as follows:
* Sarcophagus body: 2.05 meters in length
* Sarcophagus material: Shell limestone (Namakata stone)

== Artifacts ==
Grave goods unearthed from the site include:
* A bronze mirror (decorated with Buddhist and animal motifs)
* Gilded bronze horse trappings
* Iron weapons
* Ornaments
* Pottery (Sue pottery)

These artifacts are currently housed in the {{ill|Tokyo National Museum|ja|東京国立博物館|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. However, it is suggested that some of the items may originate from neighboring Kofuns within the cluster.

<gallery>
File:王墓山古墳 (倉敷市) 出土 画文帯仏獣鏡.JPG|Bronze mirror<br>{{small|Exhibited at Tokyo National Museum}}
File:王墓山古墳 (倉敷市) 竪矧広板鋲留衝角付冑.JPG|Iron helmet with rivets<br>{{small|Tokyo National Museum}}
File:王墓山古墳 (倉敷市) 出土 鐘形杏葉.JPG|Bell-shaped horse gear<br>{{small|Tokyo National Museum}}
File:王墓山古墳 (倉敷市) 広口壺 (J-7646).JPG|Sue pottery jar<br>{{small|Tokyo National Museum}}
File:王墓山古墳 (倉敷市) 出土 須恵器 蓋付・須恵器 高台付椀.JPG|Sue pottery lidded vessels and high-footed bowls<br>{{small|Tokyo National Museum}}
</gallery>

== Cultural Properties ==
=== Okayama Prefecture Designated Cultural Properties ===
* Historic Site
** Ōbosan Kofun - Designated on March 27, 1959<ref name="岡山県">[http://www.pref.okayama.jp/cgi-bin/bunka/culture/controller/client/resultDetail.cgi?id=336 Ōbosan Kofun] (Okayama Prefecture “Cultural Properties of Okayama”).</ref>.

== Nearby Sites ==
* {{ill|Tatetsuki Site|ja|楯築墳丘墓|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} - One of the largest {{ill|Yayoi|ja|弥生時代|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} Kofuns in Japan.
* Nihata Temple Site - Ruins of an ancient temple.

